1626
02:15:13,687 --> 02:15:16,428
of the Game Awards, Jeff Keighley.

1627
02:15:24,379 --> 02:15:28,141
Hello everyone, surprise. How you doing?

1628
02:15:28,141 --> 02:15:32,463
Alright, well this is a really special moment for me.

1629
02:15:32,463 --> 02:15:37,906
Because back in 2007, Shigeru Miyamoto won the GDC Lifetime Achievement Award.

1630
02:15:37,906 --> 02:15:46,890
And he told Time Magazine that the obvious objective of video games is to entertain people by surprising them with new experiences.

1631
02:15:46,890 --> 02:15:50,892
Tim Schafer is a guy who specializes in the new.

1632
02:15:55,405 --> 02:15:56,005
Tim of Legend!

1633
02:15:56,005 --> 02:16:02,006
Tim of Legend!

1634
02:16:02,006 --> 02:16:05,987
I have been playing Tim's games for so long, since I was a little kid.

1635
02:16:05,987 --> 02:16:08,207
And he specializes in the new.

1636
02:16:08,207 --> 02:16:16,149
He bursts new worlds, brainstorms new characters and architects new experiences, time and time again.

1637
02:16:16,149 --> 02:16:21,010
Tim is one of our gaming industry's most original and creative thinkers.

1638
02:16:21,010 --> 02:16:23,470
He's also, of course, one of the funniest.

1639
02:16:26,053 --> 02:16:32,541
Now, at a time when the breadth and depth of content made by this industry can be misrepresented,

1640
02:16:32,541 --> 02:16:41,812
Tim's fun, colorful, and comedic games are more important than ever.

1641
02:16:44,713 --> 02:16:51,716
Now, I first came across Tim's work when I was very young, about 12 years old, because

1642
02:16:51,716 --> 02:16:58,099
between schoolwork, I'd play LucasArts Adventure Games home in Canada, where Tim got his start

1643
02:16:58,099 --> 02:17:03,861
with a $27,000 a year salary, working on some of the earliest adventure games.

1644
02:17:03,861 --> 02:17:08,203
And of course, there was The Secret of Monkey Island, where he learned about game design

1645
02:17:08,203 --> 02:17:10,884
from the legendary Ron Gilbert.

1646
02:17:10,884 --> 02:17:11,824
Let's hear it for Monkey Island.

1647
02:17:16,098 --> 02:17:22,985
And one of my favorites, Day of the Tentacle, which he designed alongside Dave Grossman.

1648
02:17:22,985 --> 02:17:27,429
I will still always remember the CD-ROM talkie version of Dot,

1649
02:17:27,429 --> 02:17:29,091
and my quest to power up the Chrono-John.

1650
02:17:29,091 --> 02:17:33,655
These are memories from many years ago, but they still stick with me.

1651
02:17:33,655 --> 02:17:37,940
Now, as I played those games, I couldn't quite believe this rich, interactive storybook

1652
02:17:37,940 --> 02:17:40,022
that I could shape with the click of a mouse.

1653
02:17:40,562 --> 02:17:43,963
And, you know, I remember me and my brother playing through those games,

1654
02:17:43,963 --> 02:17:46,504
trying to figure out the puzzles, the inventory items,

1655
02:17:46,504 --> 02:17:50,625
and often resorting to CompuServe to get hints to figure out how to get through

1656
02:17:50,625 --> 02:17:53,966
these incredible games that Tim built many decades ago.

1657
02:17:53,966 --> 02:17:56,946
Now, as Tim's career progressed at LucasArts,

1658
02:17:56,946 --> 02:18:01,548
he started designing his own games like Full Throttle.

1659
02:18:01,548 --> 02:18:01,928
Yes.

1660
02:18:01,928 --> 02:18:07,329
And Grim Fandango, which is celebrating an anniversary this year.

1661
02:18:09,392 --> 02:18:12,494
Now, these seminal games help cement Tim's signature style,

1662
02:18:12,494 --> 02:18:15,235
rich, quirky worlds with funny talking characters

1663
02:18:15,235 --> 02:18:16,975
and challenging puzzles.

1664
02:18:16,975 --> 02:18:20,857
Now, one of the things that I most admire about Tim

1665
02:18:20,857 --> 02:18:22,638
is how over a 30 year career,

1666
02:18:22,638 --> 02:18:25,479
he's never built games based on what genre

1667
02:18:25,479 --> 02:18:27,400
is trending in the market.

1668
02:18:27,400 --> 02:18:30,181
He builds what's in his heart.

1669
02:18:30,181 --> 02:18:31,221
And we love you for it, Tim.

1670
02:18:35,950 --> 02:18:41,434
And Tim has put everything on the line time and again in pursuit of his art.

1671
02:18:41,434 --> 02:18:53,522
Today he runs his own independent studio, Double Fine, right here in San Francisco.

1672
02:18:53,522 --> 02:18:54,463
